<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8"?>
<worksheet xml:id="activity-distance-from-home"
  xmlns:xi="http://www.w3.org/2001/XInclude">

  <title>Activity: Distance from Home</title>


  <!-- ===================================================
       PAGE 1: Interpreting a given graph
       =================================================== -->
  <page>
    <exercise xml:id="ex-interpret-graph">
      <title>Interpreting Distance-Time Graphs</title>
      <introduction>
        <p>
          The qualitative graph below represents a student's car journey from campus to a coffee
          shop and back over a period of time. Let <m>t</m> be the time elapsed since leaving
          home, and let <m>D</m> be the student's distance from home. The graph is divided into
          five distinct intervals labeled A, B, C, D, and E.
        </p>
        <figure xml:id="fig-distance-given">
          <caption>A qualitative distance-time graph of a car journey with five labeled intervals.</caption>
          <image xml:id="img-distance-given" width="75%">
            <shortdescription>A piecewise linear graph with five segments labeled A through E. Segment A rises gradually, B is flat, C rises steeply, D is flat at a higher level, and E falls steeply back to zero.</shortdescription>
            <latex-image>
              \begin{tikzpicture}[scale=1.2]
                \draw[black, thick, ->] (0,0) -- (8.5,0) node[right] {$t$ (time)};
                \draw[black, thick, ->] (0,0) -- (0,4.5) node[above] {$D$ (distance)};
                \draw[blue, ultra thick] (0,0)   -- (2.0,1.0) node[midway, above left,  black] {A};
                \draw[blue, ultra thick] (2.0,1.0) -- (3.5,1.0) node[midway, above,      black] {B};
                \draw[blue, ultra thick] (3.5,1.0) -- (4.5,3.5) node[midway, above left,  black] {C};
                \draw[blue, ultra thick] (4.5,3.5) -- (6.5,3.5) node[midway, above,      black] {D};
                \draw[blue, ultra thick] (6.5,3.5) -- (8.0,0)   node[midway, above right, black] {E};
                \draw[dashed, gray] (2.0,0) -- (2.0,1.0);
                \draw[dashed, gray] (3.5,0) -- (3.5,1.0);
                \draw[dashed, gray] (4.5,0) -- (4.5,3.5);
                \draw[dashed, gray] (6.5,0) -- (6.5,3.5);
              \end{tikzpicture}
            </latex-image>
          </image>
        </figure>
      </introduction>

      <task xml:id="ex-interpret-a" workspace="0.8in">
        <statement>
          <p>
            Identify the independent and dependent variables in this scenario and justify your
            reasoning.
          </p>
        </statement>
      </task>

      <task xml:id="ex-interpret-b" workspace="0.8in">
        <statement>
          <p>
            Given that the student is driving a car, what real-world behavior could explain the
            horizontal line during interval B?
          </p>
        </statement>
      </task>

      <task xml:id="ex-interpret-c" workspace="0.8in">
        <statement>
          <p>
            Compare the speed of the car during interval A to its speed during interval C. How does
            the graph visually communicate this difference?
          </p>
        </statement>
      </task>

      <task xml:id="ex-interpret-d" workspace="1.0in">
        <statement>
          <p>
            Describe what is occurring during interval D and interval E in the context of the story.
          </p>
        </statement>
      </task>
    </exercise>
  </page>

  <!-- ===================================================
       PAGE 2: Sketching a graph from a story
       =================================================== -->
  <page>
    <exercise xml:id="ex-sketch-graph">
      <title>Sketching Distance-Time Scenarios</title>
      <introduction>
        <p>
          Read the story below carefully and construct a corresponding qualitative graph.
        </p>
        <p>
          <em>Scenario:</em> An individual leaves home to go for a morning run.
          <ol>
            <li><p>They start by jogging at a steady, moderate pace for 10 minutes.</p></li>
            <li><p>Suddenly, they realize they might have dropped their keys. They stop completely
            and search their pockets for 2 minutes.</p></li>
            <li><p>They turn around and walk slowly back toward home for 5 minutes before finally
            spotting their keys on the ground.</p></li>
            <li><p>They pause for 1 minute to pick up the keys and tie their shoe.</p></li>
            <li><p>Once ready, they sprint very fast straight back home to make up for the lost
            time.</p></li>
          </ol>
        </p>
      </introduction>

      <task xml:id="ex-sketch-variables">
        <statement>
          <p>
            Identify the independent and dependent variables for your graph, including appropriate
            units.
          </p>
          <p>
            <em>Independent variable:</em> <fillin characters="40"/>
          </p>
          <p>
            <em>Dependent variable:</em> <fillin characters="40"/>
          </p>
        </statement>
      </task>

      <task xml:id="ex-sketch-draw">
        <statement>
          <p>
            Sketch a qualitative graph on the axes below that illustrates the entire scenario.
            Label each segment of your graph to correspond with the phases of the journey.
          </p>
          <figure xml:id="fig-sketch-axes">
            <caption>Blank axes for sketching the runner's distance from home over time.</caption>
            <image xml:id="img-sketch-axes" width="80%">
              <shortdescription>Blank coordinate axes with Time on the horizontal axis and Distance from Home on the vertical axis, for student sketching.</shortdescription>
              <latex-image>
                \begin{tikzpicture}[scale=1.5]
                  \draw[black, thick, ->] (0,0) -- (8.5,0) node[right] {Time};
                  \draw[black, thick, ->] (0,0) -- (0,4.5) node[above] {Distance from Home};
                \end{tikzpicture}
              </latex-image>
            </image>
          </figure>
        </statement>
      </task>

      <task xml:id="ex-sketch-intercepts" workspace="1.0in">
        <statement>
          <p>
            In the context of a journey starting and ending at home, what do the horizontal
            intercepts (the <m>t</m>-intercepts) represent on this graph?
          </p>
        </statement>
      </task>
    </exercise>
  </page>

</worksheet>
